body:
I finally have an example of the problem that the call from within the Viewport.update to Gdx.gl.glViewport has for me (at least once it gets down to ScalingViewport). 

If a window is created with dimensions of 1280x720, but during the resize you make the Stage dimensions 640x360 using this sequence:

``` java
stage.getViewport().update(640, 360, false);
camera.setToOrtho(false, 640, 360);
camera.position.set(0f, 0f, 0.0f);
camera.update();
batch.setProjectionMatrix(camera.combined);
```

Then the rendering to the Batch for the application will not work properly without a second call to glViewport. The first attached screenshot is the result without the second call to glViewport. 
![normalviewport](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1960777/2856965/9508c4a2-d171-11e3-8403-7e1e01deeb1d.jpg)

The second is after adding this call:

``` java
Gdx.gl.glViewport(0, 0, 1280, 720);
```

![withsecondglviewport](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1960777/2856968/9ffa0b14-d171-11e3-9fd2-4278293dcd68.jpg)

The second result is the expected one, where the camera is virtually 640x360. 

The root problem is that I don't really understand why you call glViewport at all within ScalingViewport, especially since the old stages never did. I don't think it is a good idea to force a second call to glViewport to get the virtual dimensions of the camera set correctly.

Am I doing something wrong?
